<div id="review_3328878719" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3328878719" />
    <a title="Sebastián Bravo Montenegro" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/85132645-sebasti-n-bravo-montenegro"><img alt="Sebastián Bravo Montenegro" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546400657p2/85132645.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3328878719?book_show_action=true">May 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sebastián Bravo Montenegro" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sebastián Bravo Montenegro" href="/user/show/85132645-sebasti-n-bravo-montenegro">Sebastián Bravo Montenegro</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780374526160" href="/book/show/81865.Ph_dre">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3328878719" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13829608227359979408">A beautiful adaptation of the Greek Tragedy that forces you to accept that love is an indomitable force that we cannot escape from. Our futile attempts to run away from it will result in our bodies being dismantled by a sea monster. <br/><br/>I always find it fascinating that Racine shifted their focus away from Hyppolitus and onto Phaedra because in the end she is an innocent bystander that becomes the instrument to punish Hyppolitus’ chastity. Similarly, Hyppolitus becomes a victim of Phaedra’s attempt </span>
  <span id="freeText13829608227359979408" style="display:none">A beautiful adaptation of the Greek Tragedy that forces you to accept that love is an indomitable force that we cannot escape from. Our futile attempts to run away from it will result in our bodies being dismantled by a sea monster. <br /><br />I always find it fascinating that Racine shifted their focus away from Hyppolitus and onto Phaedra because in the end she is an innocent bystander that becomes the instrument to punish Hyppolitus’ chastity. Similarly, Hyppolitus becomes a victim of Phaedra’s attempt to save her dignity. And then you have Oenone, probably the most interesting and complex character whose loyalty ends up killing her mistress. After all the deaths, you are left wondering, why must we always punish the innocent and force them to become aggressors? <br /><br />I will always have a soft spot for tragedies because they embody everything that I want theater to be: ridiculous, grandiose, and merciless.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13829608227359979408" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


